  "signature": "ed25519:b7e3d1f9a2c4e6b8d0f2a4c6e8b0d2f4a6c8e0b2d4f6a8c0e2b4d6f8a0c2e4b6",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation software must be version-controlled and validated against known benchmarks; requiredLevel 2 per risk level 3 COU.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R1 was used under a validated installation qualified per ISO 13485 QMS. Software version, solver settings, and script files are archived in the sponsor's document management system. Benchmark verification against NAFEMS LE1 and LE10 plate problems confirmed solver accuracy to within 0.5%. Achieved level 3 (documented QMS-controlled environment with benchmark verification)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Code verification must confirm correct implementation of governing equations through benchmark or manufactured solutions.",
      "rationale": "The FEA solver was verified against the method of manufactured solutions for linear elastic beam bending and contact problems. Results matched analytical solutions to within 0.3% for displacement and 1.1% for peak stress. Code verification documentation is archived and reviewed by an independent analyst."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study required; discretization error must be quantified and shown to be below 5% for all QoIs.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was performed with four mesh densities (element edge lengths 0.5 mm, 0.75 mm, 1.0 mm, 1.5 mm) for both the screw and the UHMWPE block. Richardson extrapolation yielded a discretization error estimate of 1.8% for stiffness and 2.3% for yield force. Final mesh (0.75 mm global, 0.3 mm at screw-block interface) was selected as the production mesh."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals must converge below 1e-6 for all load steps; energy balance checked.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear load steps converged with force residuals below 1e-7 and displacement residuals below 1e-8. Energy balance was verified at each load increment. No spurious hourglassing or zero-energy modes were detected. Achieved level 2."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs and boundary conditions must be independently reviewed; analyst training documented.",
      "rationale": "All model inputs, boundary conditions, and material assignments were independently reviewed by a second qualified analyst prior to submission runs. Analyst training records (FEA methods, ASME V&V 40 awareness) are on file. A pre-analysis checklist was completed and archived. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model physics (contact, material nonlinearity, large deformation) must be justified relative to the COU; simplifications documented.",
      "rationale": "The model uses nonlinear contact (augmented Lagrangian) between screw and UHMWPE block, bilinear isotropic hardening for titanium alloy (Ti-6Al-4V), and large-deformation kinematics (NLGEOM ON). Simplifications (no thread geometry detail, rigid fixation at block base) are documented with sensitivity analyses showing <2% effect on QoIs. Model form is consistent with published FDA guidance and peer-reviewed literature for F1717 FEA."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs must be traceable to measurements or certified material datasheets; uncertainty quantified.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties (E = 114 GPa, σ_y = 880 MPa, tangent modulus = 1.14 GPa) are sourced from ASTM F136 and confirmed by tensile coupon testing of production-lot material. UHMWPE block properties are per ASTM F648. Geometric inputs are derived from CMM measurements of production screws (n=3). Input uncertainty was propagated via Monte Carlo (1000 samples); coefficient of variation on stiffness QoI was 2.1%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens must be representative production parts; traceability to lot and dimensional inspection required.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were drawn from two production lots. Each screw was dimensionally inspected (CMM) and confirmed within drawing tolerances. Lot traceability records are archived. Specimens span two independent laboratories, providing inter-laboratory variability data. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions must replicate the COU environment; multiple loading rates or environmental conditions required at level 3.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed per ASTM F1717 at room temperature (23 ± 2 °C) in ambient air at a single displacement rate (5 mm/min). While the standard protocol is faithfully followed, only a single test condition (rate, temperature) was evaluated. This falls short of the required level 3, which demands at least two environmental or rate conditions to bracket in-vivo variability. This gap is documented as a known limitation of the current validation dataset; a supplemental elevated-temperature test series is planned."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs used in validation simulations must match experimental specimen properties; equivalency formally demonstrated.",
      "rationale": "Material properties and geometry used in the validation FEA runs were set to match the measured values from the actual test specimens (specimen-specific simulations for 3 of 11 constructs; population-mean inputs for the remaining 8). Equivalency was formally verified via a parameter-matching table reviewed by the study sponsor and FDA liaison. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (percent difference and E/uval) must be computed for all QoIs; acceptance bounds pre-specified.",
      "rationale": "Pre-specified acceptance bounds (<10% mean percent difference, E/uval < 1.96) were documented in the V&V plan prior to testing. All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) met both criteria. Statistical uncertainty in experimental measurements (inter-specimen CV 3–6%) was incorporated into E/uval calculation. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs must be directly linked to the clinical or regulatory decision; linkage documented.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are the primary mechanical endpoints required by FDA guidance for pedicle screw 510(k) submissions under ASTM F1717. Their clinical relevance (construct rigidity for fusion, failure load relative to physiologic loads) is documented in the V&V plan with references to published biomechanical literature. Achieved level 3."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must be shown to be sufficiently representative of the intended COU geometry, loading, and boundary conditions.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity uses the identical screw design, block material, and loading configuration as the COU submission. Because the validation experiment is by construction the same as the COU test scenario, the assessment team concluded that formal evaluation of this factor introduces no additional information beyond what is already captured in the Output Comparison and Test Conditions factors. Accordingly, a separate factor-level assessment was not conducted. The team notes that this factor is effectively subsumed by the direct correspondence between validation and COU — however, no explicit graduated evidence matrix was completed and no requiredLevel or achievedLevel was assigned."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-accepted",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 credibility factors were formally assessed. Eleven factors met or exceeded their required levels. One factor (Test conditions) achieved level 2 against a required level 3, reflecting the single-condition test protocol; this gap is mitigated by the close correspondence between the ASTM F1717 standard conditions and anticipated in-vivo loading rates, and by the low sensitivity of QoIs to displacement rate demonstrated in a supplemental literature review. The thirteenth factor (Relevance of the validation activities to the COU) was not formally assessed, as the assessment team judged it inapplicable given the direct identity of validation and COU scenarios — however, this judgment was not encoded as 'not-applicable' in the factor record. Overall credibility is judged sufficient to support a Medium assurance level decision for a Class II device at model risk level 3.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
